---
import SiteLayout from "../../../layouts/SiteLayout.astro";

const schema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "mainEntity": [
    {"@type":"Question","name":"What is risk tolerance in investing?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Risk tolerance is your ability and willingness to endure declines in the value of your investments. It depends on your financial situation, investment timeline, income stability, and emotional comfort with market volatility. Understanding your risk tolerance helps you choose an asset allocation that you can stick with through market ups and downs, which is critical for long-term investment success."}},
    {"@type":"Question","name":"How is my risk profile determined?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Your risk profile is determined by evaluating multiple factors: investment time horizon, reaction to market losses, income stability, investment experience, financial goals, existing savings, and comfort with volatility. This quiz scores your answers across 10 questions and maps your total score to one of five profiles: Conservative, Moderately Conservative, Moderate, Moderately Aggressive, or Aggressive. Each profile has a recommended asset allocation."}},
    {"@type":"Question","name":"What asset allocation should I use for my risk profile?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Asset allocation depends on your risk profile. Conservative investors typically use 20-30% stocks and 60-70% bonds. Moderate investors use a classic 60/40 stock/bond split. Aggressive investors may allocate 80-90% to stocks with minimal bonds. The right allocation balances growth potential with your ability to stay invested during downturns. A common rule of thumb is subtracting your age from 110 to get your stock percentage, but your personal risk tolerance matters more."}},
    {"@type":"Question","name":"Should I change my risk tolerance over time?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Yes, your risk tolerance naturally shifts as your life circumstances change. As you approach retirement, most investors gradually shift toward more conservative allocations. Major life events like marriage, home purchase, job changes, or inheritance can also affect your risk capacity. It is good practice to reassess your risk tolerance every 1-2 years or after any significant financial change. However, avoid changing your allocation in response to short-term market movements."}},
    {"@type":"Question","name":"What is the difference between risk tolerance and risk capacity?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Risk tolerance is your emotional willingness to accept investment losses — how you feel when your portfolio drops 20%. Risk capacity is your financial ability to absorb losses without affecting your lifestyle or goals. A young high-earner might have high risk capacity (decades to recover) but low risk tolerance (panics during drops). Ideally, your investment strategy accounts for both. This quiz evaluates both dimensions across its 10 questions."}},
    {"@type":"Question","name":"Can I be too conservative with my investments?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Yes. Being too conservative is one of the biggest risks for long-term investors. If your portfolio returns less than inflation (historically ~3%), your purchasing power actually decreases over time. A 30-year-old with a 100% bond portfolio would likely fall far short of retirement goals. Conservative allocations are appropriate for short time horizons (under 5 years) or retirees drawing income, but most working-age investors need meaningful stock exposure for long-term wealth building."}},
    {"@type":"Question","name":"What are model portfolios and should I use ETFs?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Model portfolios are pre-built investment allocations designed for specific risk profiles. They typically use low-cost index ETFs to achieve broad diversification. ETFs like VTI (total US stock market), VXUS (international stocks), BND (US bonds), and VNQ (real estate) are popular building blocks. Using ETFs keeps costs extremely low (0.03-0.20% expense ratios) while providing instant diversification across thousands of securities. Most robo-advisors and financial advisors use similar ETF-based model portfolios."}},
    {"@type":"Question","name":"How often should I rebalance my portfolio?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Most experts recommend rebalancing once or twice per year, or when your allocation drifts more than 5% from your target. For example, if your target is 60% stocks and a bull market pushes it to 67%, you would sell stocks and buy bonds to return to 60/40. Rebalancing forces you to sell high and buy low systematically. Over-rebalancing (monthly or more) can trigger unnecessary taxes and trading costs. Many robo-advisors handle rebalancing automatically."}}
  ]
};

export const meta = {
  title: "Risk Tolerance Quiz",
  description: "Take this 10-question investment risk assessment to discover your risk profile, recommended asset allocation, and model ETF portfolio matched to your tolerance.",
  category: "tool",
  published: "2026-03-21",
};
---

