  { q: "Should I change my risk tolerance over time?", a: "Yes, your risk tolerance naturally shifts as your life circumstances change. As you approach retirement, most investors gradually shift toward more conservative allocations. Major life events like marriage, home purchase, job changes, or inheritance can also affect your risk capacity. Reassess every 1-2 years or after any significant financial change. Avoid changing your allocation in response to short-term market movements." },
  { q: "What is the difference between risk tolerance and risk capacity?", a: "Risk tolerance is your emotional willingness to accept investment losses — how you feel when your portfolio drops 20%. Risk capacity is your financial ability to absorb losses without affecting your lifestyle or goals. A young high-earner might have high risk capacity but low risk tolerance. Ideally, your investment strategy accounts for both. This quiz evaluates both dimensions." },
